column3:
We are trying to find out about your level of physical activity from the last 7 days (in the last
week). This includes sports or dance that make you sweat or make your legs feel tired, or games
that make you breathe hard, like tag, skipping, running, climbing, and others.
Remember:
1. There are no right and wrong answers — this is not a test.
2. Please answer all the questions as honestly and accurately as you can — this is very
important.

 - Sweets like ice cream, chocolate, doughnuts, cookies, cake, candy, ice cream
 - Starches like white bread, rolls, pasta, and rice
 - Salty snacks like chips, pretzels, and crackers
 - Fatty foods like steak, bacon, hamburgers, cheeseburgers, pizza, and French fries
 - Sugary drinks like soda pop

How often does your child disobey time limits you set for online use?
How often does your child neglect household chores to spend more time online?
How often does your child prefer to spend time online rather than with the rest of your family?
How often does your child form new relationships with fellow online users?
How often do you complain about the amount of time your child spends online?
How often do your child's grades suffer because of the amount of time he or she spends online?
How often does your child check his or her e-mail before doing something else?
How often does your child seem withdrawn from others since discovering the Internet?
How often does your child become defensive or secretive when asked what he or she does online?
How often have you caught your child sneaking online against your wishes?
How often does your child spend time along in his or her room playing on the computer?
How often does your child receive strange phone calls from new "online" friends?
How often does your child snap, yell, or act annoyed if bothered while online?
How often does your child seem more tired and fatigued than he or she did before the Internet came along?
How often does your child seem preoccupied with being back online when off-line?
How often does your child throw tantrums with your interference about how long he or she spends online?
How often does your child choose to spend time online rather than doing once enjoyed hobbies and/or outside interests?
How often does your child become angry or belligerent when your place time limits on how much time he or shes is allowed to spend online?
How often does your child choose to spend more time online than going out with friends?
How often does your child feel depressed, moody, or nervous when off-line which seems to go away once back online?

column7: Have you ever heard of marijuana (grass, pot) or hashish (has, hash oil)?
Have you ever used marijuana (grass, pot) or hashish (hash, hash oil)?
Have you ever sniffed a substance (glue, aerosols, etc.) to get high?
Have you ever used tranquillizers or sedatives (without a doctor's prescription) (e.g. benzodiazepines such as valium or xanax;barbiturates, barbs or downers such as amytal, or seconal)?
Have you ever used amphetamines (speed), methamphetamine (crystal meth), or desoxyn?
Have you ever used LSD (acid)?
Have you ever used magic mushrooms or other hallucinogens (excluding LSD)?
Have you ever used crack?
Have you ever used cocaine?
Have you ever used relevin?
Have you ever used heroin?
Have you ever used narcotics (e.g. opium, morphine, codeine)?
Have you ever used ecstasy (MDMA)?
Have you ever used ketamine (Ket, K) or Phencyclidine (PCP, or angel dust)?
Have you ever used GHB or liquid ecstasy?
Have you ever used anabolic steroids?
On how many occasions IN YOUR WHOLE LIFETIME have you used marijuana (grass, pot) or hashish (hash, hash oil)?
On how many occasions OVER THE LAST 12 MONTHS have you used marijuana (grass, pot) or hashish (hash, hash oil)?
On how many occasions OVER THE LAST 30 DAYS have you used marijuana (grass, pot) or hashish (hash, hash oil)?
On how many occasions OVER THE LAST WEEK have you used marijuana (grass, pot) or hashish (hash, hash oil)?
Please indicate if you have used marijuana (grass, pot) or hashish (hash, hash oil) on a weekly basis OVER A 12 MONTH PERIOD or in an excessive or problematic way IN YOUR LIFETIME?
Do you abuse more than one drug at a time when you use marijuana / hashish?
Can you get through the week without using marijuana / hashish (unless you require it for medical reasons)?
Are you always able to stop using marijuana / hashish when you want?
Have you had "blackouts" or "flashbacks" as a result of marijuana / hashish use?
Do you ever feel bad about your marijuana / hashish abuse?
Does your spouse (or parents) ever complain about your involvement with marijuana/ hashish?
Has marijuana / hashish abuse ever created problems between you and your spouse?
Have you ever lost friends because of your use of marijuana / hashish?
Have you ever neglected your family or missed work because of your use of marijuana / hashish?
Have you ever been in trouble at work because of marijuana / hashish abuse?
Have you ever lost a job because of marijuana / hashish abuse?
Have you ever gotten into fights when under the influence of marijuana / hashish?
Have you engaged in illegal activities in order to obtain marijuana / hashish?
Have you ever been arrested for possession of marijuana / hashish?
Have you ever experienced withdrawal symptoms as a result of heavy marijuana / hashish intake?
Have you had medical problems as a result of your marijuana / hashish use (e.g. memory loss, hepatitis, convulsions, bleeding, etc.)?
Have you ever gone to anyone for help for a marijuana / hashish problem?

column7:
Controllability - Most Severe Past 1 Month (CSSRS1_018)
Could/can you stop thinking about killing yourself or wanting to die if you want to?
column8: 1 = Easily able to control thoughts, 2 = Can control thoughts with little difficulty, 3 = Can control thoughts with some difficulty, 4 = Can control thoughts with a lot of difficulty, 5 = Unable to control thoughts, 0 = Does not attempt to control thoughts

column5:
Section: Intensity of Ideation

The following features should be rated with respect to the most severe type of ideation (i.e. from 1-5 from above, with 1 being the least severe and 5 being the most severe). Ask about the time he/she was feeling the most suicidal.
column6:
Section: Suicidal Ideation

Ask questions 1 and 2. If both are negative, proceed to "Suicidal Behavior" sections. If the answer to question 2 is "yes", ask questions 3, 4 and 5. If the answer to question 1 and/or 2 is "yes", complete "Intensity of Ideation" section.
column7:
Deterrants - Most Severe Lifetime (CSSRS1_019)
Are there things- anyone of anything (e.g. family, religion, pain of death) - that stopped you from wanting to die or acting on thoughts of committing suicide?
column8: 1 = Deterrents definitely stopped you from attempting suicide, 2 = Deterrents probably stopped you, 3 = Uncertain that deterrents stopped you, 4 = Deterrents most likely did not stop you, 5 = Deterrents definitely did not stop you, 0 = Does not apply

Elevated Mood
column8: 0=Absent, 1=Mildly or possibly increased, 2=Definite subjective elevation optimistic self-confident cheerful appropriate to content, 3=Elevated inappropriate to content humorous, 4=Euphoric inappropriate laughter singing

column7: Increased Motor Activity or Energy
column8: 0=Absent, 1=Subjectively increased, 2=Animated gestures increased, 3=Excessive energy hyperactive at times restless (can be calmed), 4=Motor excitement continuous hyperactivity (cannot be calmed)

column7: Sexual Interest
column8: 0=Normal not increased, 1=Mildly or possibly increased, 2=Definite subjective increase, 3=Spontaneous sexual content elaborates on sexual matters hypersexual, 4=Overt sexual acts

column7: Sleep
column8: 0=No decrease in sleep, 1=Sleeping less than normal amount by up to one hour, 2=Sleeping less than normal by more than one hour, 3=Decreased need for sleep, 4=No need for sleep at all

column7: Irritability
column8: 0=Absent, 1=Subjectively increased, 2=Irritable at times recent episodes of anger or annoyance, 3=Frequently irritable short curt, 4=Hostile uncooperative

column7: Speech: Rate & Amount
column8: 0=No increase, 1=Feel talkative, 2=Increased rate or amount at times verbose at times, 3=Push consistently increased rate and amount, 4=Pressured uninterruptedly continuous speech

column7: Language: Thought Disorder
column8: 0=Absent, 1=Circumstantial mild distractibility quick thoughts, 2=Distractible loses goal of thought change topics frequently racing thoughts, 3=Flight of ideas tangentially difficult to follow rhyming echolalia, 4=Incoherent communication impossible

column7: Content
column8: 0=Normal, 1=Questionable plans new interests, 2=Special project(s) hyper religious, 3=Grandiose or paranoid ideas ideas of reference, 4=Delusions hallucinations

column7: Disruptive or Aggressive Behavior
column8: 0=Absent, 1=Sarcastic loud at times guarded, 2=Demanding threats, 3=Threats shouting, 4=Assaultive destructive

column7: Appearance
column8: 0=Appropriate dress and grooming, 1=Minimally unkempt, 2=Poorly groomed moderately disheveled overdressed, 3=Disheveled partly clothed garish make-up, 4=Completely unkempt decorated bizarre garb

column7: Insight
column8: 0=Present, admits illness agrees with need for treatment 1=Possibly ill, 2=Admits behavior change but denies illness 3=Admits possible change in behavior but denies illness, 4=Denies any behavior change
